        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Ezekiel &#38; Bernheim&#44;<lb/>
                Auctioneers&#44;<lb/>
                Nos 134 Main and 31 Hammond Streets.<lb/></p>
            <p>Cincinnati&#44; March 9<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1886.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>Rev. S. Morais.<lb/>
                Philadelphia&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>My esteemed Friend&#8212;It has been a long time since<lb/> I have availed myself of this pleasure&#44; and sincerely hope<lb/> these few lines may reach you&#8212;finding your dear self our<lb/> dear Nina and the rest of your dear family in the enjoy&#45;<lb/>ment of health&#44; we all continue to be moving about as us&#45;<lb/>ual. I must say thank God that I am feeling somewhat better<lb/> than formerly and gaining flesh&#44; whether it portends for a<lb/> good or evil omen God only knows. I hope for the best.<lb/></p>
            <p>My valued friend. from what I read in Eastern weeklies&#44; you<lb/> do not have time to get sick &#44; as you appear to be &#34;on the go&#34;<lb/> either writing&#44; speaking or <sic>travelling</sic>&#44; You have your &#34;hobby&#34;&#44;<lb/> and I trust you may succeed. It is indeed a praisewor&#45;<lb/>thy undertaking&#44; we sometimes pull down <sic>delapidated</sic> houses<lb/>to build new structures&#44; but as our <hi rend="underline">Western</hi> house is not very<lb/>old or <sic>delapidated</sic> I trust it will not be necessary to pull it<lb/> down to build an Eastern house&#44; hence&#44; I sincerely trust you<lb/> may be able to build your new structure on a foundation<lb/> that has never been perverse to the advancement of the<lb/> most liberal ideas for the perpetuation of Judaism&#44; in our<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>blessed country. I am well aware that you have under&#45;<lb/>taken a herculean task&#44; from purely honest motives&#44; and I am<lb/> not of those who <hi rend="underline">cannot</hi> <hi rend="underline">do</hi>&#44; and do not wish others to do. You<lb/> have no doubt read my articles in the &#34;American Hebrew&#34; and<lb/> &#34;Messenger&#34; which gave ample reasons why the New York Prepa&#45;<lb/>ratory Department could not be continued&#44; hence I could not say<lb/> <del>an</del> more and now will not tax you reading a re&#45;iteration on that<lb/> subject&#44; as as matter of course we cannot know your success<lb/> of last Sundays Meeting at New York. There is material and<lb/> money enough in New York and Philadelphia alone to maintain<lb/> a college East without interfering with congregations who<lb/> now comprise the Union&#44; it is <hi rend="underline">the</hi> <hi rend="underline">Union</hi> that I desire<lb/> to be perpetuated for far higher purposes than mere Edu&#45;<lb/>cational. I am aware that a man as truly honest in<lb/> all particulars relating to the welfare of Judaism in this<lb/> country as is my dear friend&#44; would not think it policy<lb/> to destroy a <del>Union&#91;&#63;&#93;</del> Union for mere partisan feelings&#44; rather<lb/> strengthen our Union that its true and legitimate functions can<lb/> be fully carried out for the good and welfare of Israel.<lb/> I trust you may be enabled to open a Collegiate de&#45;<lb/>partment in New York and at least sustain it until our<lb/>council shall meet in Pittsburgh July 1878; if God willing I<lb/> trust to be there&#44; and that such a <sic>reconcilliation</sic> may<lb/> be effected&#44; that we may again adopt the New York<lb/> School as a preparatory department of the Hebrew Union College<lb/> Well my page <del>us&#91;&#63;&#93;</del> is full&#44; and I must close. May God bless<lb/> you and your dear ones. As Ever  truly &#38;c <hi rend="underline">Jacob</hi> <hi rend="underline">Ezekiel</hi><lb/></p>
            </body>
